{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649021"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:00:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:00:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18340"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18340"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.7,0.13,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11058"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79328"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11058"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18340"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64650"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7470"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25657"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27149"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79328"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following describes the primary function of the calcaneal tuberosity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Articulation with the talus","Attachment site for the Achilles tendon","Insertion of the tibialis posterior tendon","Origin of the flexor digitorum brevis muscle","Support for the plantar fascia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe calcaneus, or heel bone, is the largest bone in the foot and plays a vital role in weight-bearing and movement. The calcaneal tuberosity is a prominent feature of the calcaneus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of the calcaneal tuberosity is as an \u003Cstrong\u003Eattachment site for the Achilles tendon\u003C/strong\u003E. This tendon connects the calf muscles to the heel bone, allowing for the transmission of forces necessary for walking, running, and jumping.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArticulation with the talus\u003C/strong\u003E - The calcaneus does articulate with the talus, but this is not the function of the tuberosity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupport for the plantar fascia\u003C/strong\u003E - The plantar fascia attaches to the calcaneus, but not specifically to the tuberosity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrigin of the flexor digitorum brevis muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle originates from the calcaneus, but not from the tuberosity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsertion of the tibialis posterior tendon\u003C/strong\u003E - This tendon inserts on the navicular and other tarsal bones, not the calcaneus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The calcaneal tuberosity serves as the attachment site for the Achilles tendon.","The calcaneal tuberosity plays a crucial role in transmitting forces from the calf muscles to the foot.","The calcaneal tuberosity is important for foot stability and movement during walking and running."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64650"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18340"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64650"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T09:31:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T09:32:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11058"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79328"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","po